  "query": "What methods are available to control disease and sea lice in Atlantic salmon farms?",
  "relevant_summary": "Evidence from action documents indicates several methods: Implementing fallowing between production cycles has been associated with lower sea lice numbers in Scotland, though an Australian study found no reduction in mortality from Amoebic Gill Disease (action_id: 1026). Deploying cleaner wrasse as natural control agents shows mixed outcomes: in Ireland, corkwing and goldsinny wrasse performed as well as chemical treatments in one controlled study, while rockcook wrasse were ineffective in a replicated, controlled study (action_id: 738). Dietary interventions, including probiotics and immunostimulants, have shown benefits: a replicated study in Scotland reported increased survival after probiotic feeding before bacterial challenges, and a replicated, controlled study in Norway reported a 28% reduction in lice with a diet containing 28% plant protein, with an additional 28% reduction when beta-glucans were added; mannan oligosaccharides also improved gut function by preventing soybean-induced enteritis (action_id: 732).",
